> That’s a net new behavior, isn’t it? I think that’s fine, but there’s some risk of breaking existing scripts (directing output to some kind of pipe).

No it isn't, not doing that broke the tests (as they capture the output via pipe) which mean it must worked like that before.
I doubled check locally the behavior as well. I think the goterm lib was coded in a very weird way which is why I missed that part as well.

The old code had:
```
func Flush() {
	for idx, str := range strings.SplitAfter(Screen.String(), "\n") {
		if idx > Height() {
			return
		}

		Output.WriteString(str)
	}

	Output.Flush()
	Screen.Reset()
}
```

That exits early as Height() should be -1 and thus always smaller
